# Reading Age Checker

Analyses any piece of text or uploaded document and returns a reading age assessment, plain-language score, and a rewritten plain-English version — helping public sector teams communicate clearly with the people they serve.

## What it does

1. Accepts pasted text or an uploaded document (PDF, Word, or plain text)
2. Calculates a Flesch-Kincaid reading age and grade level
3. Produces a Flesch Reading Ease score with an interpreted label (e.g. "Difficult – suitable for university graduates")
4. Identifies specific problem areas: long sentences, complex words, passive voice, and jargon
5. Rewrites the content at a target reading age (default: age 9, the GOV.UK recommended level, configurable)
6. Returns a structured report with the original text annotated alongside the plain-English version

## Why this matters

The UK average reading age is 9. Government guidance recommends writing for a reading age of 9–11. Many public sector documents — letters, policy guidance, service pages, consultation documents — are written at a reading age of 14 or above, creating barriers for citizens who most need access to public services.

This flow helps any team — comms, policy, service design, legal — check and improve their content before it goes out.

## Inputs

| Input | Type | Required | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Text or document | String or file | Yes | Paste directly or upload PDF/DOCX/TXT |
| Target reading age | Integer | No | Default: 9 (GOV.UK recommended). Accepts 8–16 |
| Output format | String | No | `report` (default) or `rewrite-only` |

## Outputs

| Output | Description |
|---|---|
| Flesch-Kincaid Reading Age | Numeric reading age (e.g. 14.2) |
| Flesch Reading Ease score | 0–100 scale with plain-English label |
| Problem areas | List of long sentences, complex words, passive constructions |
| Plain-English rewrite | Full rewrite at target reading age |
| Summary report | Structured markdown report combining all outputs |

## Applicable standards and guidance

- [GOV.UK content design guidance](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/content-design/writing-for-gov-uk) — recommends reading age 9
- [WCAG 2.2 – 3.1.5 Reading Level](https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/Understanding/reading-level) — AAA criterion
- [Plain English Campaign guidelines](https://www.plainenglish.co.uk/)
- NHS England content style guide — recommends reading age 11 or below

## Sector applicability

| Sector | Use case |
|---|---|
| Local government | Resident letters, planning notices, FOI responses, web content |
| NHS / health | Patient information, appointment letters, discharge summaries |
| Central government | Policy documents, consultation papers, guidance notes |
| Education | Parent communications, school prospectuses |
| Housing associations | Tenancy agreements, service charge statements |

## Platform implementations

| Platform | Status | Folder |
|---|---|---|
| Flowise | Available | [`flowise/`](./flowise/) |

## Limitations

- Reading age scores are approximations based on sentence and word length; they do not capture semantic complexity
- The plain-English rewrite should be reviewed by a human before publication — AI rewrites can change meaning unintentionally
- Non-English text is not supported in this version
- Very short inputs (under 100 words) produce unreliable scores
